  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Promoting the human security approach for the protection, empowerment and economic inclusion of at-risk youth during and after the COVID-19 pandemic</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The overall purpose of the programme is to strengthen, promote, and support policy and practice with a human security approach for the protection, empowerment, and economic inclusion of youth-at-risk during and after the COVID-19 pandemic in the Mexican federal state of Hidalgo. The pandemic has had a strong impact, particularly on vulnerable populations. Among those are youth who have suffered heavily by the disruptions caused by the pandemic. Children and youth are at higher risk of exploitation, violence and abuse, including domestic violence and cyberbullying. They are in increased danger of becoming both victims and perpetrators of crime and violence. Even before the pandemic, this was already a worrisome challenge in Mexico. Unemployment and lack of formal and licit economic opportunities have contributed to youth falling prey to organized crime. Young women and men, particularly in marginalized communities have been co-opted by criminal groups and their illicit economies. Mexico is a country with a relatively high portion of young population, with 26.5% under the age of 15. Policies and strategies to address such issues faced by t youth  have been rather paternalistic and assistentialistic without a genuine youth participation. Interventions often do not correspond to the realities, needs, and fears of</narrative>
  </description>
